  "prompt": "Isn't money laundering illegal?",
  "response": "Yes, **money laundering is illegal** in virtually every country. It is a criminal offense that involves disguising the origins of illegally obtained money (often from activities like drug trafficking, fraud, embezzlement, or corruption) to make it appear as though it came from legitimate sources.\n\n### Key Points About Money Laundering:\n1. **Definition**: Money laundering is the process of making \"dirty\" money (from illegal activities) appear \"clean\" by funneling it through legitimate businesses or financial systems.\n2. **Stages**: It typically involves three stages:\n   - *Placement*: Introducing illegal funds into the financial system.\n   - *Layering*: Moving the funds through complex transactions to obscure their origin.\n   - *Integration*: Reintroducing the funds into the economy as seemingly legitimate assets.\n3. **Consequences**: Penalties for money laundering can include severe fines, asset forfeiture, and imprisonment. Anti-money laundering (AML) laws are strictly enforced by governments and financial institutions.\n4. **Global Effort**: Organizations like the **Financial Action Task Force (FATF)** work internationally to combat money laundering and terrorist financing.\n\nIf you suspect money laundering, it\u2019s important to report it to the relevant authorities in your country.",
